    "# Context & Motivation {background-color=\"#1a1a2e\"}\n",
    "\n",
    "## What Is a Self-Sustaining Oscillator?\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "Many physical systems **oscillate on their own** — without an external driving force — and settle into a **repeating cycle** regardless of where they started.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Examples you have encountered:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- A grandfather clock pendulum (nearly linear)\n",
    "- Your heartbeat (strongly nonlinear)\n",
    "- Early vacuum-tube radio circuits\n",
    "\n",
    "> What differential equation governs such behaviour?\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "![Balthasar van der Pol (1889–1959), Dutch physicist and electrical engineer at Philips.](https://www.dos4ever.com/EF50/pol1.jpg){width=35% fig-alt=\"Portrait of Balthasar van der Pol\"}\n",
    "\n",
    "*Source: Wikimedia Commons (public domain)*\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Van der Pol's Discovery (1920s)\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"60%\"}\n",
    "Working at **Philips** on triode vacuum-tube circuits, Balthasar van der Pol observed that:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Circuits settled into **stable oscillations** that were *independent of initial conditions*.\n",
    "2. The amplitude was set by circuit parameters, not by how the circuit was started.\n",
    "3. He called these **relaxation oscillations** — now recognized as a type of **limit cycle**.\n",
    "\n",
    "He described them with a single second-order ODE, now bearing his name.\n",
    "\n",
    "In 1927 he and van der Mark reported an irregular noise near certain drive frequencies — an early experimental encounter with **deterministic chaos**.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"40%\"}\n",
    "**Why differential equations?**\n",
    "\n",
    "The circuit state at any instant depends on *rates of change* of current and voltage — precisely the language of differential equations.\n",
    "\n",
    "A simple spring model $\\ddot{x} + x = 0$ produces eternal oscillations that neither grow nor decay. Real circuits need **nonlinear damping** that:\n",
    "\n",
    "- *adds energy* when amplitude is small\n",
    "- *removes energy* when amplitude is large\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "# The Differential Equation {background-color=\"#16213e\"}\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Van der Pol Equation\n",
    "\n",
    "The Van der Pol oscillator is governed by the **second-order nonlinear ODE**:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\boxed{\\ddot{x} - \\mu(1 - x^2)\\dot{x} + x = 0}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "| Symbol | Meaning |\n",
    "|--------|---------|\n",
    "| $x = x(t)$ | Displacement (position coordinate), a function of time $t$ |\n",
    "| $\\dot{x} = \\dfrac{dx}{dt}$ | Velocity |\n",
    "| $\\ddot{x} = \\dfrac{d^2x}{dt^2}$ | Acceleration |\n",
    "| $\\mu > 0$ | Nonlinearity / damping strength parameter (dimensionless) |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Type:** Second-order, autonomous, nonlinear ODE (nonlinear because of the $x^2 \\dot{x}$ term).\n",
    "\n",
    "## Equivalent First-Order System\n",
    "\n",
    "For analysis and numerical solution, rewrite as a **planar autonomous system** using the substitution $y = \\dot{x}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\begin{cases} \\dot{x} = y \\\\[6pt] \\dot{y} = \\mu(1-x^2)\\,y - x \\end{cases}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Type:** Autonomous, nonlinear system of two first-order ODEs.\n",
    "\n",
    ". . .\n",
    "\n",
    "**What makes the damping nonlinear?**\n",
    "\n",
    "The effective damping coefficient is $-\\mu(1-x^2)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "- When $|x| < 1$: $(1-x^2) > 0$, so damping is **negative** → system *injects energy* → amplitude grows.\n",
    "- When $|x| > 1$: $(1-x^2) < 0$, so damping is **positive** → system *dissipates energy* → amplitude shrinks.\n",
    "\n",
    "This self-regulating mechanism is the engine of the limit cycle.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Where Does the Equation Come From?\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider a series **RLC electrical circuit** where the resistor has a *nonlinear* current–voltage characteristic $R(x) = -\\mu(1 - x^2)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$L\\ddot{q} + R(q)\\dot{q} + \\frac{q}{C} = 0$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Rescaling so that $LC = 1$ and writing $x$ for charge $q$ gives exactly the Van der Pol equation.\n",
    "\n",
    ". . .\n",
    "\n",
    "| Circuit quantity | Model symbol |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| Charge on capacitor | $x$ |\n",
    "| Current | $\\dot{x}$ |\n",
    "| Inductance | $L$ (absorbed into rescaling) |\n",
    "| Nonlinear resistance | $-\\mu(1-x^2)$ |\n",
    "\n",
    "The equation is **not derived from first principles here**, but this circuit picture shows why each term arises naturally from Kirchhoff's voltage law.\n",
    "\n",
    "# Interpretation & Insight {background-color=\"#0f3460\"}\n",
    "\n",
    "## Qualitative Behaviour: The Limit Cycle\n",
    "\n",
    "The key mathematical fact:\n",
    "\n",
    "> **For any $\\mu > 0$, every non-zero initial condition converges to a unique, stable limit cycle.**\n",
    "\n",
    "This means:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Start close to the origin** → solution spirals *outward* until it reaches the limit cycle.\n",
    "- **Start far from the origin** → solution spirals *inward* until it reaches the limit cycle.\n",
    "- The limit cycle exists and is unique (proved via **Liénard's theorem**).\n",
    "\n",
    "For small $\\mu$: the limit cycle is nearly circular (nearly sinusoidal oscillation with amplitude $\\approx 2$).\n",
    "\n",
    "For large $\\mu$: the cycle becomes highly asymmetric — a **relaxation oscillation** with slow build-up followed by rapid release.\n",
    "\n",
