    "## What Do the Solutions Tell Us?\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
    "**Mathematical features**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Unique unstable equilibrium** at $(x, \\dot{x}) = (0, 0)$: the origin is a spiral source — any perturbation grows.\n",
    "- **Globally stable limit cycle**: a closed orbit in the phase plane that all trajectories approach.\n",
    "- **No exact analytic solution** exists in general (proved by Panayotounakos et al., 2003).\n",
    "- Period for small $\\mu \\approx 2\\pi + O(\\mu^2)$; for large $\\mu \\approx (3 - 2\\ln 2)\\mu$.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
    "**Real-world meaning**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The **heartbeat** is a biological Van der Pol–type oscillator: it has a natural rhythm (limit cycle) that restores itself after disturbance.\n",
    "- **Vocal fold vibration** uses coupled Van der Pol oscillators; the limit cycle amplitude corresponds to the loudness of phonation.\n",
    "- The **FitzHugh–Nagumo model** of neural action potentials is a direct generalization of this equation.\n",
    "- In engineering: explains why vacuum-tube circuits lock onto a stable frequency regardless of noise or startup transients.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::::\n",
